---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="What is an atom?" description="A beginner guide to atoms, protons, neutrons and electrons">
  <style>
    .article-header { background: #26215C; border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .tags { display: flex; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .tag { font-size: 11px; padding: 3px 10px; border-radius: 999px; font-weight: 500; }
    .article-title { font-size: 28px; font-weight: 600; color: #EEEDFE; line-height: 1.3; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .article-desc { font-size: 15px; color: #AFA9EC; line-height: 1.6; }
    .body-text { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.8; color: #1a1a2e; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .callout { background: #f5f5f5; border-left: 3px solid #FAC775; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .callout-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a2e; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .callout-text { font-size: 14px; color: #555; line-height: 1.6; }
    .section-title { font-size: 20px; font-weight: 600; color: #26215C; margin-bottom: 12px; margin-top: 2rem; }
    .diagram-box { background: #26215C; border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; }
    .diagram-caption { font-size: 13px; color: #888; text-align: center; margin-top: -1rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .particle-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .particle-card { border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.25rem; text-align: center; }
    .particle-symbol { font-size: 28px; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 6px; }
    .particle-name { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 500; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .particle-detail { font-size: 12px; opacity: 0.8; line-height: 1.5; }
    .topic-tags { display: flex; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2rem; }
    .topic-tag { font-size: 12px; padding: 5px 12px; border-radius: 999px; }
  </style>

  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#412402;">Beginner</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#26215C;">Atomic Structure</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">What is an atom?</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Everything you can see, touch, and breathe is made of atoms. Here's what they actually are and what's inside them.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">
    Atoms are the smallest units of matter that retain the chemical properties of an element. They are unimaginably small — a single strand of human hair is about a million atoms wide. Despite their size, atoms have an internal structure made of even smaller particles.
  </p>

  <h2 class="section-title">Inside an atom</h2>

  <div class="diagram-box">
    <svg width="300" height="300" viewBox="0 0 300 300">
      <circle cx="150" cy="150" r="30" fill="#534AB7"/>
      <circle cx="150" cy="150" r="18" fill="#3C3489"/>
      <circle cx="143" cy="145" r="6" fill="#FAC775"/>
      <circle cx="157" cy="145" r="6" fill="#FAC775"/>
      <circle cx="150" cy="157" r="6" fill="#AFA9EC"/>
      <ellipse cx="150" cy="150" rx="70" ry="25" fill="none" stroke="#5DCAA5" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4"/>
      <ellipse cx="150" cy="150" rx="70" ry="25" fill="none" stroke="#5DCAA5" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4" transform="rotate(60 150 150)"/>
      <ellipse cx="150" cy="150" rx="70" ry="25" fill="none" stroke="#5DCAA5" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4" transform="rotate(120 150 150)"/>
      <circle cx="220" cy="150" r="8" fill="#9FE1CB"/>
      <circle cx="185" cy="89" r="8" fill="#9FE1CB"/>
      <circle cx="115" cy="89" r="8" fill="#9FE1CB"/>
      <text x="150" y="240" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="#AFA9EC">nucleus</text>
      <text x="230" y="145" font-size="11" fill="#9FE1CB">e⁻</text>
      <text x="188" y="84" font-size="11" fill="#9FE1CB">e⁻</text>
      <text x="100" y="84" font-size="11" fill="#9FE1CB">e⁻</text>
      <text x="140" y="148" font-size="9" fill="#FAC775">p⁺</text>
      <text x="152" y="148" font-size="9" fill="#FAC775">p⁺</text>
      <text x="146" y="161" font-size="9" fill="#AFA9EC">n</text>
    </svg>
  </div>
  <p class="diagram-caption">A simplified model of a lithium atom — 3 protons, 3 neutrons, and 3 electrons</p>

  <h2 class="section-title">The three particles</h2>

  <div class="particle-grid">
    <div class="particle-card" style="background:#EEEDFE;">
      <div class="particle-symbol" style="color:#534AB7;">p⁺</div>
      <div class="particle-name" style="color:#26215C;">Proton</div>
      <div class="particle-detail" style="color:#534AB7;">Positive charge<br/>Found in nucleus<br/>Mass = 1 amu</div>
    </div>
    <div class="particle-card" style="background:#f5f5f5;">
      <div class="particle-symbol" style="color:#444;">n</div>
      <div class="particle-name" style="color:#1a1a2e;">Neutron</div>
      <div class="particle-detail" style="color:#666;">No charge<br/>Found in nucleus<br/>Mass = 1 amu</div>
    </div>
    <div class="particle-card" style="background:#E1F5EE;">
      <div class="particle-symbol" style="color:#085041;">e⁻</div>
      <div class="particle-name" style="color:#085041;">Electron</div>
      <div class="particle-detail" style="color:#0F6E56;">Negative charge<br/>Orbits nucleus<br/>Mass ≈ 0 amu</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">
    The protons and neutrons cluster together in the center of the atom called the nucleus. The nucleus is incredibly dense — it contains almost all of the atom's mass but takes up only a tiny fraction of its volume. If an atom were the size of a football stadium, the nucleus would be the size of a marble at the center.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Key concept: atomic number</div>
    <div class="callout-text">The number of protons in an atom defines what element it is. Carbon always has 6 protons. Oxygen always has 8. This number is called the atomic number and is unique to each element. Change the number of protons and you have a completely different element.</div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-title">Electron shells</h2>

  <div class="diagram-box">
    <svg width="320" height="200" viewBox="0 0 320 200">
      <circle cx="160" cy="100" r="15" fill="#534AB7"/>
      <text x="160" y="105" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#FAC775">nucleus</text>
      <circle cx="160" cy="100" r="40" fill="none" stroke="#AFA9EC" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3"/>
      <circle cx="160" cy="100" r="70" fill="none" stroke="#5DCAA5" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3"/>
      <circle cx="160" cy="100" r="95" fill="none" stroke="#9FE1CB" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3"/>
      <circle cx="160" cy="60" r="6" fill="#AFA9EC"/>
      <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="6" fill="#AFA9EC"/>
      <circle cx="160" cy="170" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <circle cx="90" cy="100" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <circle cx="218" cy="68" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <circle cx="218" cy="132" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <circle cx="102" cy="68" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <circle cx="102" cy="132" r="6" fill="#5DCAA5"/>
      <text x="205" y="58" font-size="10" fill="#AFA9EC">Shell 1: max 2e⁻</text>
      <text x="230" y="105" font-size="10" fill="#5DCAA5">Shell 2: max 8e⁻</text>
      <text x="258" y="130" font-size="10" fill="#9FE1CB">Shell 3: max 18e⁻</text>
    </svg>
  </div>
  <p class="diagram-caption">Electron shells — each shell holds a maximum number of electrons</p>

  <p class="body-text">
    Electrons occupy the space around the nucleus in regions called electron shells. The first shell holds a maximum of 2 electrons, the second holds 8, and the third holds up to 18. Atoms fill their shells from the inside out. The electrons in the outermost shell are called valence electrons and they determine how an atom bonds with others.
  </p>

  <p class="body-text">
    In a neutral atom the number of protons equals the number of electrons — the positive and negative charges balance out. If an atom gains or loses electrons it becomes an ion — a charged particle. This is the basis of ionic bonding and many chemical reactions.
  </p>

  <div class="topic-tags">
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#534AB7;">Atomic structure</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#633806;">Beginner</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Protons</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E6F1FB;color:#0C447C;">Electrons</span>
  </div>
</Layout>